post_text:
Virtual Athenaeum: Today we discuss the virtue of friendship, read the book, A Bargain for Frances by: Russell Hoban, and make a friendship necklace.

If you joined us last time, you can use your left-over clay from the 'Four Greek Loves' lesson to make your friendship necklace. Or, to make the clay for your friendship necklace, you will need:
-1 cup cornstarch
-1 cup school glue
-2 Tbs vinegar (can sub lemon juice)
-2 Tbs oil (vegetable, baby, or coconut, etc.)
-toothpicks
-cookie cutters (optional)

For more videos or to register for After-School Athenaeum for Fall 2020-21, please visit:
www.GreatHeartsAmerica.org/Athenaeum

post_text:
Virtual Athenaeum: Do you have a lot of small crayon pieces left over at the end of the school year? Learn how you can recycle old crayons and make them good as new again!

**Be sure to have an adult help with this project!**

All you need to make your own crayon creation is:
old, broken crayons (with the paper removed)

If using the oven:
muffin tin (or silicone baking mold)
muffin tin liners (or non-stick spray)

Bake at about 200 degrees for about 10 min

If using the microwave:
Microwave-safe bowl, dish or mold

Microwave on low heat for approximately 5-6 minutes (stop and stir every 2 minutes)

**Be careful after crayons are melted as they will be very hot. Wait until your crayons are completely cooled before taking them out of the mold and using them. Remember, be sure to have an adult help with this project!**

For more videos or to register for After-School Athenaeum 2020-21, please visit:
www.GreatHeartsAmerica.org/Athenaeum

Register before May 31st and save $75!

Virtual Athenaeum: In todays’ lesson, scholars discover the art of Spanish artist Joan Miro who learned that painting what made him happy was the most genuine way for him to express his creativity. The step by step activity will allow the scholars to express their own creativity and bring some happy expression into their day.

To create your own Joan Miro-inspired masterpiece, you will need:
Paper
Black marker or pen
Crayons or colored pencils

We will continue to post Virtual Athenaeum through the month of June so be sure to look out for our next video!

For more videos and to learn more about After-School Athenaeum, please visit:
www.GreatHeartsAmerica.org/Athenaeum

Virtual Athenaeum: Have you ever wondered about the science behind blowing bubbles? Today we'll make a batch of homemade bubble solution and learn how to make a bubble-wand for giant bubbles!

All you need to make your own bubble solution is:
water, dish soap, sugar

You can get creative with your bubble-wand design! Some materials that may help are:
stick, pencil, string, pipe cleaners, hanger, wire, shoe lace, etc.
What did you use to make your bubble-wand?

post_text:
Great Hearts Academies plans to extend spring break at all of our campuses through the week of March 16th. There will be no regular school or after-school activities during this week. We plan to resume classes on March 23, 2020. You can stay informed on our website: https://www.greatheartsamerica.org/coronavirus/
Should we need to extend again, we will tell you as soon as we have made that decision.

It was magic today on the Cicero campus for our second day of Unity in the Community. Our talented Prep students played the piano and sang at all of our Archway lunches. Prep mentors visited the Archway kids at lunch as well.

Today was a good day for Cicero.

The gym that we share with Cicero Prep is getting a face lift thanks to your AZ Public School Tax Credit dollars! Archway uses the gym for PE, community building events, athletics, concerts and much more!

We were also able to purchase three new Centurion canopies to use at athletic events, meets, tournaments, in the quad and anywhere else we want to show our Centurian pride! Did you know that Archway 5th graders can play middle school sports at Cicero Prep and that your tax credit dollars support our athletic program, extracurriculars and clubs?

Thank you for all your support! You can take the credit now for the 2019 tax year! www.archwaycicero.org/support

I truly wanted to give them the gift of self confidence in their artistic expression before they left our school.
